<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="256" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,681,1302,1365]" box="[151,295,1339,1365]" pageId="3" pageNumber="256">
(
<figureCitation box="[159,287,1339,1365]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 33–40" captionStart-1="FIGURES 41–46" captionStartId-0="8.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionStartId-1="9.[151,264,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox-0="[169,1422,199,1911]" captionTargetBox-1="[195,1386,195,1865]" captionTargetId-0="figure-25@8.[166,1422,181,1920]" captionTargetId-1="figure-19@9.[191,1396,181,1882]" captionTargetPageId-0="8" captionTargetPageId-1="9" captionText-0="FIGURES 33–40. Loneura maracaensis García Aldrete (Holotype male). 33. Front view of head. 34. Left forewing. 35. Right forewing. 36. Left hindwing. 37. Right hindwing. 38. Fore- leg. 39. Mid- leg. 40. Hind- leg. Scales in mm." captionText-1="FIGURES 41–46. Loneura maracaensis García Aldrete (Holotype male). 41. Phallosome (image). 42. Phallosome (drawing). 43. Hypandrium (image). 44. Hypandrium (drawing). 45. Clunium, epiproct and right and left paraprocts (image). 46. Left paraproct and (drawing). Abbreviations: aes, anterior endophallic sclerites; ep, external parameres; ms, mesal sclerite; les, lateral endophallic sclerite; pes, posterior endophallic sclerites; st, side strut. Scales in mm." pageId="3" pageNumber="256">Figs 33–46</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1410,1977]" box="[151,1078,1410,1437]" pageId="3" pageNumber="256">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,289,1410,1436]" pageId="3" pageNumber="256">Description</emphasis>
. As in the original description (
<bibRefCitation author="Garcia Aldrete, A. N." box="[643,939,1411,1437]" pageId="3" pageNumber="256" pagination="303 - 311" refId="ref9612" refString="Garcia Aldrete, A. N. (2004) New species of Psocoptera (Insecta) from Brazil. Anales del Instituto de Biologia, Universidad Nacional Autonoma de Mexico, Serie Zoologia, 75 (2), 303 - 311." type="journal article" year="2004">García Aldrete, 2004: 306</bibRefCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[950,1065,1411,1437]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1921,1945]" captionTargetBox="[159,1431,193,1889]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,181,1897]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Loneura cavernicola sp. nov. (Holotype male). 1. Front view of head. 2. Lacinial tip. 3. Antennae. 4. Left forewing. 5. Left hindwing. 6. Right forewing. 7. Right hindwing. 8. Fore- leg. 9. Mid- leg 10. Hind- leg. Scales in mm." pageId="3" pageNumber="256">Figs 6–10</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1410,1977]" pageId="3" pageNumber="256">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,424,1447,1473]" pageId="3" pageNumber="256">Taxonomy update.</emphasis>
Phallosome (
<figureCitation box="[583,719,1447,1473]" captionStart="FIGURES 41–46" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[195,1386,195,1865]" captionTargetId="figure-19@9.[191,1396,181,1882]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 41–46. Loneura maracaensis García Aldrete (Holotype male). 41. Phallosome (image). 42. Phallosome (drawing). 43. Hypandrium (image). 44. Hypandrium (drawing). 45. Clunium, epiproct and right and left paraprocts (image). 46. Left paraproct and (drawing). Abbreviations: aes, anterior endophallic sclerites; ep, external parameres; ms, mesal sclerite; les, lateral endophallic sclerite; pes, posterior endophallic sclerites; st, side strut. Scales in mm." pageId="3" pageNumber="256">Figs 41, 42</figureCitation>
), side struts anteriorly not fused, V-shaped, widening distally, fused to external parameres, these stout, anteriorly narrow and sclerotized, medially wide, ending in a lobed projection bearing a field of pores. Four pairs of endophallic sclerites; an anterior pair proximally curved inward with pointed apices, distally narrow and almost straight, ending in rounded tips; mesal pair strongly sclerotized, stout, proximally and distally with rounded tips, medially slightly curved, wide in almost its entire length; lateral pair heart shaped; posterior pair, elongate, proximally wide, concave with two rounded projections, slender distally, ending in an elongate outward curved tip, hook shaped.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
